# =============================================================================
# Stillwater · Yoga Studio — Environment Variables Example
# =============================================================================
#
# Copy this file to `.env` (dev) or `.env.local` (production) and adjust
# the values for your environment.
#
#   cp .env.example .env        # local development
#   cp .env.example .env.local  # production (mounted by docker-compose.prod.yml)
#
# The codebase reads exactly TWO env vars at runtime:
#   1. DATABASE_URL  — read by Prisma (prisma/schema.prisma)
#   2. NODE_ENV      — read by src/lib/db.ts (controls the global singleton)
#
# Next.js + Bun also read a few built-in vars (NEXT_TELEMETRY_DISABLED,
# NEXT_PHASE, HOSTNAME, PORT) — these are set automatically by the Dockerfile
# and are documented below for reference.
#
# This file is safe to commit to version control. It contains NO secrets —
# only placeholders and documentation. Real values live in `.env` or
# `.env.local`, both of which are gitignored.
# =============================================================================

# ── Database ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# The connection string for Prisma. Two modes are supported:
#
#   SQLite (default, dev):
#     DATABASE_URL="file:./db/stillwater.db"
#     The path is relative to the project root. `prisma db push` creates
#     the file on first run. No server process — Prisma reads the file
#     directly.
#
#   PostgreSQL (production, optional):
#     DATABASE_URL="postgresql://user:password@host:5432/database?schema=public"
#     To switch, also change `provider` to "postgresql" in prisma/schema.prisma
#     and run `bunx prisma migrate deploy` (NOT `db push`) in production.
#
# SQLite is sufficient for a single-model marketing site (the Lead model
# for form submissions). Migrate to Postgres when you need concurrent
# writers, managed backups, or Postgres extensions.
DATABASE_URL="file:./db/stillwater.db"

# ── Runtime mode ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Set by Next.js automatically. Read by src/lib/db.ts to control the Prisma
# client global singleton (prevents hot-reload connection leaks in dev).
# Usually you don't set this manually — `bun run dev` sets it to
# "development", `bun run build` + `bun run start` set it to "production".
# NODE_ENV="development"

# ── Next.js built-ins (set automatically by Docker, documented for reference) ─
# These are read by Next.js / Bun internals, not by the app code. The
# Dockerfile sets them; you usually don't need to set them in .env.

# Disable Next.js anonymous telemetry (0 or 1). Set to 1 in production.
# NEXT_TELEMETRY_DISABLED=1

# Next.js build phase. Set automatically during `next build`. Don't set
# manually unless you know what you're doing.
# NEXT_PHASE=phase-production-build

# Server bind address and port. Defaults to 0.0.0.0:3000. Override only
# if you're running behind a reverse proxy on a different port.
# HOSTNAME=0.0.0.0
# PORT=3000

# ── Future: when you add auth, payments, or email ───────────────────────────
# The codebase currently has NO auth, NO payments, and NO transactional email.
# When you add them, uncomment and set these:
#
# Auth.js v5 (when you add a member portal):
#   AUTH_SECRET="<32+ char random string — generate with: openssl rand -base64 32>"
#   AUTH_URL="https://your-domain.com"
#
# Resend (transactional email — when you automate Iris's hand-written replies):
#   RESEND_API_KEY="re_..."
#
# Upstash Redis (when you outgrow the in-memory rate limiter):
#   UPSTASH_REDIS_REST_URL="https://...upstash.io"
#   UPSTASH_REDIS_REST_TOKEN="..."
#
# Postgres (when you outgrow SQLite):
#   DATABASE_URL="postgresql://user:password@host:5432/database?schema=public"
#   DATABASE_URL_UNPOOLED="postgresql://user:password@host:5432/database?schema=public"
